metadata.name: Slumbers #227
metadata.description:
Generative abstract artwork that explores forms, shapes, coloring and brushwork.

Options:

- press 'f' to turn off paper-like texture (recommended for print on hi-quality paper)
- press 's' to save the PNG image of the current view
- press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to save hi-res PNG images

Colors and textures might differ slightly on some devices due to the heavy use of low alpha blending. Calibrated and tested on Firefox 107.0 & Chrome 107.0.5304.107 on Win10 x64 Intel machine.

Created using p5js.

@VolatileMoods, November, 2022.

metadata.name: CSS Crystals✨ #7
metadata.description:
This 3D HTML + CSS based work utilizes only a limited amount of javascript to construct the scene and facilitate interactive controls. 🚫 <canvas>! Continuing the collab with my alternate identity HTMLCSS.TEZ

The practice of layering many graphic shapes and gradients with a chaotic mix of blending modes has been with me since my first years of photoshop in my youth. It's a familiar, friendly technique. Yet, I've rarely played with it outside photoshop. Here I take the opportunity to apply this abstract blending technique in a manner that alludes to reality: refracting crystals.

These generated crystals are not based in fact but imagination. They are illustrative of the magic and wonder some people associate with real life minerals and rocks. They blend together with impossible color changes only possible in the virtual.

Each individual crystal element can be one of these blend modes (with chance):
difference (9/16), exclusion (2/16), hard-light (2/16), color-dodge (1/16), overlay (1/16), normal (1/16)

Controls:
Play/Pause - [Space]
Rotate - [Click + Drag]
Move - [Shit + Click + Drag]

Minter's Reward: 1/3 Secondary royalties

metadata.name: Sweeping #73
metadata.description:
Sweeping is a piece in which I explore the uses of noise fields. Using them in the most cliche way possible, but trying to make something unique out of that.

What started out as an innocent weekend project grew out to be quite the piece, which is why I am publishing it here.



Sweeping uses the GPU of your machine for its shading, which means it won't run particularly well on mobile devices. My recommended way of viewing this piece is on a PC with a dedicated GPU.

---

- Double Click to open a User Interface
- In the UI, you can toggle the paper texture and export

---

Made with p5js + webgl by Wouter Missler, 2022.

metadata.name: Lineas #17
metadata.description:
Búscame entre mis letras por que en ellas siempre voy a estar
y en los versos de mis poemas mi corazón escucharás...

Lee cada palabra que encuentres donde quieres buscar
esas que ya conoces y que además te hacen extrañar.
Si te emocionan sueña siempre con algo más, no llores
por que existe un camino donde las letras tienen su punto y final.

El amor es un poema o un milagro terrenal, es la magia
que nos envuelve a los que nos podemos enamorar.
Amar cuesta y cuando se ama duele, se sufre, se llora
por el ser amado, eso es lo que tu alma atesora.

Cada verso que escribo lleva en su contenido un significado,
una promesa, un abrazo entre líneas y un beso de enamorado...

AMOR ENTRE LÍNEAS.
poema de De Lorenzo Román.

-----

Press 'e' to export a 1640 x 2000 pixels PNG

Press 'h' to export a 3280 x 4000 pixels PNG

-----



Artwork by @cristianrohr 2022.

Made with P5js and <3.

metadata.name: Rolling Hills at Sundown #8
metadata.description:
"Rolling Hills at Sundown" is a project inspired by a road trip to the Southwest United States my family made this summer. We made stops at around 15 national parks, each with different rock formations, from the peaks of the Rocky Mountains to the depths of the Grand Canyon. The last park we stopped at was White Sands National Park in New Mexico. The rolling dunes seemed to go on forever, and the sand was so fine that you could slide down the dunes like snow.

Made with p5.js

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: print size @ 3000px x 3000px

metadata.name: A Study of Primes #6
metadata.description:
“Some numbers, even large ones, have no factors - except themselves, of course, and 1. These are called prime numbers, because everything they are starts with themselves. They are original, gnarled, unpredictable, the freaks of the number world.” ― Richard Friedberg

My first project and brief study into the world of Prime Numbers.

A curated list of interesting prime numbers, some are palindromes, others have sequential patterns, others are just....pretty. 

Humans constant search for patterns among the chaos continues! 

Each Prime Number has Three Attributes

-Prime Number
-Number of Digits
-Random Neon Color (For Fun!)

Donations will go towards funding other bigger and more interesting data/art/science projects! Prob will do a giveaway or something silly for the supporters! 

I dunno really know where this is headed lmao...thanks for looking! 

Hope you have a great rest of your day! :)

metadata.name: Sands of Time #68
metadata.description:
We've been recently inspired to do this work while being on vacation, in one the most vibrant cities in the world, in the hot pot and intermixture of cultures, terrains and soundscapes. Borrowing the metaphors of sand, from Negarestani's "Cyclonopedia", and of time from "Chronosis", these living substances, we wanted to represent some of the vibes, that have been implanted into our gritty enduring nomadic existence.

This work was created to celebrate #fxhashturnsone event.

The earnings are partly donated to:
- #TezosStandsWithUkraine
- #Tezos4Iran

Made with love, AI and p5.js code

November, 2022
Julia V & YulikolaY

metadata.name: Journeys #7
metadata.description:
As #fxhashturnsone, it seemed apt to release one of my old WIPs, Journeys, to showcase my own journey in the creative coding space. The piece tries to recreate subway maps in a generative fashion, and is meant to reflect the journeys of people as they move and interact with each other. Some journey alongside each other before branching off, while others only meet at the end of their journeys. Even more will never meet at all.   

SAs #fxhashturnsone, it seemed apt to release one of my old WIPs, Journeys, to showcase my own journey in the creative coding space. The piece tries to recreate subway maps in a generative fashion, and is meant to reflect the journeys of people as they move and interact with each other. Some journey alongside each other before branching off, while others only meet at the end of their journeys. Even more will never meet at all.   

Several flow fields randomly determine the flow of each line, while attractors cause lines to be naturally drawn to certain places on the map. The code checks to ensure that lines do not overlap (but they can intersect!) and ensures a minimum distance between adjacent lines. Several code chunks are referenced in the comments which calculate intersections between points / lines.

THIS CODE IS VERY MUCH RAW AND UNFINISHED! It reflects my own growth in the space, where I started out, and where I'm heading towards. Happy birthday fxHash! I hope everyone finds their own Journey out there.
